In recent years, accurate sales forecasting has been a fundamental requirement for effec-
tive supply chain management. Organisations rely on demand predictions to determine
the amount of inventory to hold, when to reorder, and how much buffer stock to keep
against uncertainty. An inaccurate estimate has a negative impact on any organisation’s
supply chain and subsequently affects its profitability. The COVID-19 pandemic showed
how quickly widespread supply chain disruptions can lead to major stockouts, resulting
in substantial loss of revenues and, in some cases, even company bankruptcies (Aratani,
2024; Fried, 2020).

However, such inventory failures are not limited to crisis events. Even under stable con-
ditions, misaligned inventory levels consistently reduce efficiency and profitability. When
stock is held in excess, organisations incur carrying costs that typically represent between
20 and 30 percent of the total inventory value (McCue, 2022). Similarly, underestima-
tion of demand leads to stockouts, lost sales, and customer dissatisfaction (Amosu et al.,
2024). It is therefore crucial for organisations to manage their inventories by taking cus-
tomer demand into account, a process that depends on the accuracy of sales forecasting.

Despite its importance, traditional forecasting methods, such as time series models and
regression-based approaches, often struggle to capture the complex, non-linear patterns
present in real-world sales data, leading to persistent inaccuracies (Tulli, 2020). While
advanced machine learning methods often achieve higher predictive performance than tra-
ditional forecasting approaches, many smaller organisations that do not have a dedicated
data science team cannot access and deploy such tools. Their implementation demands
significant computational resources, model training expertise, and ongoing maintenance
(Kumar et al., 2023).

This project addresses this gap through a Design Science Research approach, by pro-
ducing a functional artefact in a real-world forecasting context (Hevner et al., 2004). The
artefact is an interactive web-based dashboard that allows the user to upload historical
sales data, select one of four predictive models, and receive a visual weekly sales forecast
alongside reasoning about the predicted numbers. It is designed to simplify the user ex-
perience by hiding the complex models behind a simple interface, allowing users without
prior data science knowledge to benefit from accurate sales forecasting.

From an academic perspective, this project also has relevance. By following the De-
sign Science Research methodology, it contributes to a growing body of research that
evaluates artefacts in real-world settings rather than producing purely theoretical out-
put (Hevner et al., 2004). This project contributes to the growing field of Explainable
Artificial Intelligence (XAI) within demand forecasting. Existing forecasting research pri-
marily focuses on improving predictive accuracy, while limited attention is given to the
interpretability and explanation of model outputs for end users (Theissler et al., 2022).
By integrating forecasting models with explanation techniques such as SHAP and Par-
tial Dependence Plots, this research aims to improve both transparency and usability of
machine learning-based forecasting systems.

The main research question guiding this project is: How can explainable AI methods
provide meaningful interpretation for demand forecasting models?

This thesis is produced as part of a collaborative group research project. Each group
member contributed to the problem definition, supplemental data collection and pre-
processing, dashboard design, and its implementation. Additionally, each member is
individually responsible for developing a separate forecasting model under identical data
conditions, with all four models integrated in the dashboard. The present thesis focuses
